sitive numbers b, c, and f. Which equation correctly expresses c in terms of b and f?", "type": "multiple_choice", "topic": "math", "section": "math", "options": ["c equals StartFraction b Over 42 f EndFraction", "c equals StartFraction b minus 42 Over f EndFraction", "c equals 42 b f", "c equals 42 minus b minus f"], "correct_answer": "A", "difficulty": "easy", "explanation": "Choice A is correct. It''s given that the equation b equals 42 c f relates the positive numbers b, c, and f. Dividing each side of the given equation by 42 f yields StartFraction b Over 42 f EndFraction equals c, or c equals StartFraction b Over 42 f EndFraction. Thus, the equation c equals StartFraction b Over 42 f EndFraction correctly expresses c in terms of b and f.\nChoice B is incorrect. This equation can be rewritten as b equals c f plus 42.\nChoice C is incorrect. This equation can be rewritten as b equals StartFraction c Over 42 f EndFraction.\nChoice D is incorrect. This equation can be rewritten as b equals 42 minus c minus f."}, {"id": "opensat-math-mcq-268", "text": "What is 10 percent sign of 370?", "type": "multiple_choice", "topic": "math", "section": "math", "options": ["27", "37", "333", "360"], "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "easy", "explanation": "Choice B is correct. 10 percent sign of a quantity means StartFraction 10 Over 100 EndFraction times the quantity. Therefore, 10 percent sign of 370 can be represented as StartFraction 10 Over 100 EndFraction left parenthesis 370 right parenthesis, which is equivalent to 0.10 left parenthesis 370 right parenthesis, or 37. Therefore, 10 percent sign of 370 is 37.\nChoice A is incorrect. This is 10 percent sign of 270, not 10 percent sign of 370.\nChoice C is incorrect. This is 90 percent sign of 370, not 10 percent sign of 370.\nChoice D is incorrect. This is 370 minus 10, not 10 percent sign of 370."}]'::jsonb);
INSERT INTO sat_tests (title, description, test_type, difficulty, length, section, is_official, time_limit_minutes, questions) VALUES ('OpenSAT Math - Easy Set 5','Official-style SAT Math practice (Easy) from OpenSAT — image-free questions only.','math','easy','medium','math',true,38,'[{"id": "opensat-math-mcq-270", "text": "d equals 16 t\nThe given equation represents the distance d, in inches, where t represents the number of seconds since an object started moving. Which of the following is the best interpretation of 16 in this context?", "type": "multiple_choice", "topic": "math", "section": "math", "options": ["The object moved a total of 16 inches.", "The object moved a total of 16 t inches.", "The object is moving at a rate of 16 inches per second.", "The object is moving at a rate of one sixteenth inches per second."], "correct_answer": "C", "difficulty": "easy", "explanation": "Choice C is correct. It\u2019s given that in the equation d equals 16 t, d represents the distance, in inches, and t represents the number of seconds since an object started moving. In this equation, t is being multiplied by 16. This means that the object\u2019s distance increases by 16 inches each second. Therefore, the best interpretation of 16 in this context is that the object is moving at a rate of 16 inches per second.\nChoice A is incorrect and may result from conceptual errors.\nChoice B is incorrect. This is the best interpretation of 16 t, rather than 16, in this context.\nChoice D is incorrect and may result from conceptual errors."}, {"id": "opensat-math-mcq-272", "text": "How many yards are equivalent to 612 inches? left parenthesis 1 yard equals 36 inches right parenthesis", "type": "multiple_choice", "topic": "math", "section": "math", "options": ["0.059", "17", "576", "22,032"], "correct_answer": "B", "difficulty": "easy", "explanation": "Choice B is correct. It\u2019s given that 1 yard equals 36 inches. Therefore, 612 inches is equivalent to 612 inches left parenthesi